dy Joyce Clarke于1435年出生在英国英格兰爾时，她的父亲John Clark I Baron Of Forde Hall41岁，母亲Lady Susan Agnes Forde42岁。她于1449年与Sir Robert George Wood of Cheshire在英国英格兰爾維布波瑞结婚。他们至少是1个女儿的父母。她去世于1480年在英国爾維布波瑞享年45岁。"},"hr":{"1435–1480":"1435.–1480.","1415–1506":"1415–1506","1420–1480":"1420–1480.","1425–Male":"1425–preminuo","1435–1496":"1435.–1496","1430–1476":"1430–1476.","1440–1480":"1440.–1480.","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1440":"1440.","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1480":"1480.","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1435":"1435.","1455":"1455","1476":"1476.","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1496":"1496","1506":"1506","1417":"1417.","1449":"1449.","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Houndstone, Somerset, England":"Houndstone, Somerset, Engleska, United Kingdom","Wybunbury, Cheshire, England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1435–1480":"1435–1480","1415–1506":"1415–1506","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1425–Male":"1425–Zesnulý","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1430–1476":"1430–1476","1440–1480":"1440–1480","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1440":"1440","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1480":"1480","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1496":"1496","1506":"1506","1417":"1417","1449":"1449","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Houndstone, Somerset, England":"Houndstone, Somerset, Anglie, United Kingdom","Wybunbury, Cheshire, England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, Anglie","Kent, England":"Kent, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1435–1480":"1435–1480","1415–1506":"1415–1506","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1425–Male":"1425–Afdød","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1430–1476":"1430–1476","1440–1480":"1440–1480","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1440":"1440","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1480":"1480","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1496":"1496","1506":"1506","1417":"1417","1449":"1449","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Houndstone, Somerset, England":"Houndstone, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Wybunbury, Cheshire, England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1435–1480":"1435–1480","1415–1506":"1415–1506","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1425–Male":"1425–Overleden","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1430–1476":"1430–1476","1440–1480":"1440–1480","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1440":"1440","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1480":"1480","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1496":"1496","1506":"1506","1417":"1417","1449":"1449","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Houndstone, Somerset, England":"Houndstone, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wybunbury, Cheshire, England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1435–1480":"1435–1480","1415–1506":"1415–1506","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1425–Male":"1425–Deceased","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1430–1476":"1430–1476","1440–1480":"1440–1480","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1440":"1440","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1480":"1480","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1496":"1496","1506":"1506","1417":"1417","1449":"1449","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Houndstone, Somerset, England":"Houndstone, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Wybunbury, Cheshire, England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clarke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Clark  .","History: This name was brought independently to New England by many bearers from the 17th century onward. Nicholas Clarke was one of the founders of Hartford, CT (coming from Cambridge, MA with Thomas Hooker) in 1635."],"variants":[{"name":"Clark","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>clerk</i>, <i>clark</i> ‘clerk, cleric, writer’ (Old French <i>clerc</i>; see   Clerc  ). The original sense was ‘man in a religious order, cleric, clergyman’. As all writing and secretarial work in medieval Christian Europe was normally done by members of the clergy, the term <i>clerk</i> came to mean ‘scholar, secretary, recorder, or penman’ as well as ‘cleric’. As a surname, it was particularly common for one who had taken only minor holy orders. In medieval Christian Europe, clergy in minor orders were permitted to marry and so found families; thus the surname could become established.","Irish (Westmeath, Mayo): in Ireland the English surname was frequently adopted, partly by translation for <i>Ó Cléirigh</i>; see   Cleary  .","Americanized form of Dutch   De Klerk   or Flemish   De Clerck   or of variants of these names, and possibly also of French   Clerc  . Compare   Clerk   2 and   De Clark  ."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Joyce Clarke was born in 1435, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Clark I Baron Of Forde Hall, was 41 and her mother, Lady Susan Agnes Forde, was 42. She married Sir Robert George Wood of Cheshire in 1449, in Wybunbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1480, in Wybunbury, Cheshire, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1435–1480":"1435–1480","1415–1506":"1415–1506","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1430–1476":"1430–1476","1440–1480":"1440–1480","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1440":"1440","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1480":"1480","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1496":"1496","1506":"1506","1417":"1417","1449":"1449","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Houndstone, Somerset, England":"Houndstone, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wybunbury, Cheshire, England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1435–1480":"1435–1480","1415–1506":"1415–1506","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1425–Male":"1425–Kuollut","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1430–1476":"1430–1476","1440–1480":"1440–1480","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1440":"1440","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1480":"1480","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1476":"147